  "reasoning": "A 2-configuration of order 1 with exactly 1 cell consists of exactly one pair, and the pairs form a partition of A. Thus A must have exactly 2 elements (one pair), so n = 2. Then k = n + 5 = 7. In a best-of-9 series, exactly k = 7 games are played if and only if, after 6 games, neither team has yet won 5 (so each has at most 4 wins), and then one team wins game 7 to reach 5. A team cannot reach 5 wins before game 7 if we are to play exactly 7 games. This means after 6 games, a possible score is 4–2 for either team; the team with 4 wins then wins game 7. Let M be the Mathletes, O the opponents. Case 1: Mathletes win the series 5–2. After 6 games, Mathletes must be 4–2. Number of sequences of 6 games with 4 M wins and 2 O wins is C(6,4) = 15. Probability of any such sequence is (2/3)^4(1/3)^2. Then Mathletes win game 7 with probability 2/3. So Case 1 probability = 15 * (2/3)^4 * (1/3)^2 * (2/3). Case 2: Opponents win the series 5–2. After 6 games, opponents must be 4–2. Number of sequences of 6 games with 2 M wins and 4 O wins is C(6,2) = 15. Probability of any such sequence is (2/3)^2(1/3)^4. Then opponents win game 7 with probability 1/3. So Case 2 probability = 15 * (2/3)^2 * (1/3)^4 * (1/3). Total probability: 15*(2/3)^4*(1/3)^2*(2/3) + 15*(2/3)^2*(1/3)^4*(1/3) = 15*(2/3)^5*(1/3)^2 + 15*(2/3)^2*(1/3)^5. Factor out 15*(2/3)^2*(1/3)^2: 15*(2/3)^2*(1/3)^2 *[(2/3)^3 + (1/3)^3] = 15*(4/9)*(1/9)*[(8/27)+(1/27)] = 15*(4/81)*(9/27) = 15*(4/81)*(1/3) = 15*(4/243) = 60/243 = 20/81.",
